column1: Strains of chicken that show only low levels of feather pecking activity appear to be less fearful than those that tend to be feather peckers , although this may be related to social motivation rather than fear ( Jones et al , 1995 ) . Although there are no strain differences in fearfulness , strains such as the White Leghorn tend to be more responsive than broiler strains when exposed to threat ( Keer - Keer et al , 1996 ) . Predation In their natural state , wild fowl will respond to overhead predation by remaining silent , crouching and freezing , whilst the response to ground predators is to call , run and fly away ( Appleby , Hughes and Elson , 1992 ) . The tendency to form groups is also as protection against predators .
